   Sweater Sales Unfair
</HL>
<DATE>
08/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Commerce Department ruled that
manufacturers in Taiwan have exported sweaters to the U.S. at
prices about 21.4% below "fair value."
   If the U.S. International Trade Commission concludes later
that the imports have injured domestic manufacturers of
man-made fiber sweaters, the government will order extra
duties under the Anti-Dumping Act to offset the price
margins.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The ITC is expected to issue its final decision in the
next few weeks on whether anti-dumping duties are required on
sweater imports from South Korea and Hong Kong, as well as
from Taiwan.
   According to the ITC, imports of man-made fiber sweaters
from all three Asian suppliers totaled nearly $1 billion last
year.
