<HL>
   Business Brief -- FundAmerica Inc.:
   Discount Buying Club Files
   For Chapter 11 Protection
</HL>
<DATE>
08/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   FundAmerica Inc., a discount buying club under
investigation by Florida authorities, filed for protection
from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy
laws.
   The company, which sells $100 annual memberships entitling
members to rebates on vacations, credit-card purchases,
long-distance telephone calls and purchases of consumer
goods, listed assets of $17,457,000 and liabilities of
$14,446,000.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   FundAmerica Inc. is owned by Fund America Holdings Ltd., a
closely held British Columbia corporation.
   Irvine, Calif.-based FundAmerica Inc. filed for
bankruptcy-law protection in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Santa
Ana, Calif. Florida authorities had filed a cease-and-desist
order against the company, charging that it is an elaborate
pyramid scheme. FundAmerica's founder had resigned in the
wake of his arrest last month on charges of organized fraud
and conducting an illegal lottery.
</TEXT>
