<HL>
   Business Brief -- Dart Drug Stores Inc.:
   Maryland Discount Retailer
   To Liquidate the Company
</HL>
<DATE>
08/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   DDRQC
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Dart Drug Stores Inc. said it will liquidate the company
because it has been unable to develop a plan of
reorganization acceptable to creditors.
   The Landover, Md., discount retailer, which owes about
$130 million, said it plans to close all 65 Fantle's
Drugstores in the Washington area by early November.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Dart Drug filed for protection from creditors under
Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code about a year ago.
The company said it plans to sell its inventory and store
leases as soon as it has authorization from the bankruptcy
court, but declined to estimate proceeds.
   The company said it owes about $24 million to its major
secured creditor Mellon Bank Corp. in Pittsburgh. Trustees
for the largest groups of unsecured bondholders are
Continental Stock Transfer &amp; Trust Co., with debt of about
$101 million, and Signet Trust Co., with about $29 million.
   In April 1989, Dart Drug changed the name of its stores to
Fantle's and tried a new store format in an effort to boost
sales and profits. Sheldon W. Fantle, chairman and chief
executive officer, said strong competition and a sluggish
economy prevented the company from fully implementing its
marketing strategy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900820-0026
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900820-0026.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Geo. A. Hormel &amp; Co.:
   Net Income Declined 12%
   In the Fiscal Third Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
08/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4D
</SO>
<CO>
   HRL
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Geo. A. Hormel &amp; Co. said its fiscal third quarter net
income dropped 12% because it had to pay high prices for
hogs.
   The Austin, Minn.-based meat processor said profit was
$12.6 million, or 16 cents a share, for the quarter ended
July 28, compared with $14.3 million, or 18 cents a share, a
year earlier. The year-earlier per-share figure is adjusted
to reflect a 2-for-1 stock split paid Jan. 31.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales rose 16% to $654.7 million from $564.0 million.
   Profit margins were hurt by the jump in the price of hogs,
which the company buys to make meat products. Although the
price of pork products jumped by some measures to a record
level in supermarkets earlier this summer, Hormel said it
still wasn't able to immediately pass along all of its
increased costs to customers.
   The price of fattened hogs was high earlier this year
because of unusually small herds. Hormel said that the supply
of hogs is gradually increasing and that its raw material
costs are moderating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900820-0025
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900820-0025.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Pioneer Electronic Corp.:
   Pretax Profit Rose 32%
   In Fiscal First Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
08/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PIO
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Pioneer Electronic Corp. said strong sales lifted its
consolidated pretax profit 32% in the first quarter ended
June 30.
   Pretax profit rose to 19.884 billion yen from 15.089
billion yen a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Net income rose 67% to 9.922 billion ($673 million) yen
from 5.955 billion yen ($404 million). Per-share net rose to
55.25 yen from 35.79 yen.
   Sales rose 31% to 141.672 billion yen ($9.6 billion) from
107.859 billion yen ($7.3 billion). Sales of laser and
compact disk players and their related software were
particularly strong, according to Pioneer.
   The value of sales abroad was also increased by the
weakness of the yen in the first quarter, compared with a
year earlier, the company said. Pioneer marked 82.044 billion
yen of sales overseas, 58% of the total.
   Pioneer didn't release a forecast for full-year results,
but said it expects sales to rise further, aided by
introduction of new products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
